@node WhatIsIt "What IS MPackMUI anyway? (or, for that matter, what is MPack?)"
                               @{b}What Is MPackMUI?@{ub}

MPackMUI is a GUI for the command line-based MPack. MPack, in case you don't
know, is a program which can convert a binary file into MIME format text, which
can then be sent as an email. Once received, the email can then be converted
back into binary format with Munpack, a program included with MPack.

I developed MPackMUI as I found encoding and decoding files, especially
multi-part files, too tedious with the the CLI. I was also looking for an
opportunity to write an application which uses MUI, and MPackMUI seemed ideal.

I've added a feature to MPackMUI which enables the automatic decoding of
multi-part files. Simply attempt to decode one of the files, and the others will
also be decoded.

@endnode

@node Requirements "Requirements..."
                                  @{b}Requirements@{ub}

To use MPackMUI, you will need:

    * OS 3.5

    * MUI V3.8 (probably works with older versions)

    * MPack/Munpack V1.5 (Aminet:comm/misc/mpack-1.5.lha)

I don't recommend running MPackMUI with older versions of MPack, as there will
almost certainly be differences in command-line structure and features.

@endnode

@node Usage "How to use MPackMUI"
                                     @{b}Usage@{ub}

Choose a topic:

    @{" How To Encode Files " link HowToEncode}
    @{" How To Decode Files " link HowToDecode}

    @{" Encode " link Encode}
    @{" Decode " link Decode}
    @{" Email  " link Email}
    @{"   NG   " link NG}

    @{" MIME Preferences" link Preferences}

See the MPack docs for more information on encoding and decoding.

@endnode

@node HowToEncode "Encoding files with MPackMUI"
                       @{b}How To Encode Files With MPackMUI@{ub}

1. Select the file you want to encode, and choose a name for the new MIME file.

2. You can optionally specify a description file, which will be included with
   the MIME text. When the text is decoded, the description file will also be
   unpacked.

3. Choose the type of file you are encoding. If you can't find the type you
   need, create a new one in the MIME preferences. (see @{" MIME preferences " link Preferences})

4. Enter a subject, or leave the field blank.

5. You can specify a maximum size for the output file(s) in bytes. If you intend
   to send the files by email later, this can be used to generate individual files
   each under, say, 1MB in size.

6. Click the encode button.

@endnode

@node HowToDecode "Decoding files with MPackMUI"
                       @{b}How To Decode Files With MPackMUI@{ub}

@{fg shine}1.@{fg text} Select the file you want to encode, and choose a directory to unpack the file
   to. If you want to decode multi-part files, collect all the files into one
   directory, and check that their names end in .01, .02 etc. Select one of the
   files, and they will all be decoded automatically.

@{fg shine}2.@{fg text} If you want to unpack text from multi-part messages, select the upper check
   gadget.

@{fg shine}3.@{fg text} If you want MPack to overwrite existing files when decoding, select the lower
   check gadget.

@{fg shine}4.@{fg text} Click the decode button.

@endnode

@node Encode ">>>>> Encoding files >>>>>"
                                @{b}Page 1 - Encode@{ub}

The `Encode' page allows you to encode a file, and save the resulting encoded
data to another file.

@{i}Input File@{ui}

Name & path of the file to encode.

@{i}Output File@{ui}

Name & path of file to write encoded file to.

@{i}Description File@{ui}

Name & path of description file to include with encoded file. Optional.

@{i}MIME Type@{ui}

Type of file being encoded.

@{i}Subject@{ui}

Subject of encoded message.

@{i}Maximum Size@{ui}

Maximum size (in bytes) of encoded files. If the encoded file comes to over this
amount, multiple files will be written with the names "outputfile.01",
"outputfile.02", "outputfile.03" etc. where outputfile is the file name
specified. Optional.

@{i}Encode Button@{ui}

Initiate encoding of the file.

@endnode

@node Decode ">>>>> Decoding files >>>>>"
                                @{b}Page 2 - Decode@{ub}

The `Decode' page allows you to decode a previously encoded file.

@{i}Input File@{ui}

Name & path of the file to decode. If you have multi-part files, collect them
all together in the same directory and check that their names end in .01, .02
etc. Select one of these, and the others will be decoded automatically.

@{i}Output Directory@{ui}

Path to write output file(s) to.

@{i}Force Overwrite@{ui}

If a decoded file has the same name as an existing file in the output directory,
and this flag is set, that file will be overwritten. Otherwise, a number will be
appended to the end of the decoded file's name.

@{i}Unpack Text@{ui}

Not sure what this does. Check the MPack docs.

@{i}Decode Button@{ui}

Initiate decoding of the file(s).

@endnode

@node Email ">>>>> Emailing encoded files >>>>>"
                                 @{b}Page 3 - Email@{ub}

The `Email' page allows you to encode a file and mail the resulting encoded data
to one or more email addresses. This feature requires "Sendmail" to be present,
or a similar program set up to work with MPack. See the MPack docs for more
information.

@{i}Input File@{ui}

Name & path of the file to encoded.

@{i}Address(es)@{ui}

List of address(es) to send the resulting encoded file to. If more than one
address is specified, separate them with spaces.

@{i}Description File@{ui}

Name & path of description file to include with encoded file. Optional.

@{i}MIME Type@{ui}

Type of file being encoded.

@{i}Subject@{ui}

Subject of encoded message.

@{i}Maximum Size@{ui}

Maximum size (in bytes) of encoded files. If the encoded file comes to over this
amount, multiple files will be written with the names "outputfile.01",
"outputfile.02", "outputfile.03" etc. where outputfile is the file name
specified. Optional.

@{i}Encode & Send@{ui}

Encode the file and send the resulting encoded file to the address(es)
specified.

@endnode

@node NG ">>>>> Posting encoded files to newsgroups >>>>>"
                                  @{b}Page 4 - NG@{ub}

The NG page allows you to encode a file and post the resulting encoded data to
one or more newsgroups. This feature requires "Postnews" to be present, or a
similar program set up to work with MPack. See the MPack docs for more
information.

@{i}Input File@{ui}

Name & path of the file to encoded.

@{i}Newsgroup(s)@{ui}

List of newsgroups to send the resulting encoded file to. If more than one
newsgroup is specified, separate them with commas. Don't include spaces in the
list.

@{i}Description File@{ui}

Name & path of description file to include with encoded file. Optional.

@{i}MIME Type@{ui}

Type of file being encoded.

@{i}Subject@{ui}

Subject of encoded message.

@{i}Maximum Size@{ui}

Maximum size (in bytes) of encoded files. If the encoded file comes to over this
amount, multiple files will be written with the names "outputfile.01",
"outputfile.02", "outputfile.03" etc. where outputfile is the file name
specified. Optional.

@{i}Encode & Post@{ui}

Encode the file and post the resulting encoded file to the newsgroup(s)
specified.

@endnode

@node Preferences "MIME Preferences..."
                                @{b}MIME Preferences@{ub}

The MIME preferences window lets you change the MIME types available for
encoding. The interface is fairly intuitive, so I won't go into too much detail.

When creating MIME types, don't end them with '*', e.g. "Audio/*", as this will
cause MPack to fail.

You can import MIME preferences from AWeb and Voyager, using the relevant menu
items. The Voyager prefs are called MIME.prefs, and can be found in the ENV:
directory. The AWeb preferences are called Browser, and can be found in a
subdrawer in ENV: (this varies from version to version, so you'll have to locate
the file yourself).

@endnode

@node Bugs "Bug Reports..."
                                  @{b}Bug Reports@{ub}

If you discover a bug whilst using MPackMUI, please report it to me as soon as
possible. If you want to report a bug, try to include with your report (if you
think it's necessary):

    * Your system setup (hardware/software running at time)

    * Circumstances leading to the problem

    * A detailed description of the problem itself (Software Failure numbers,
      erratic behaviour, etc.)

    * Circumstances after the problem (system stability, locked up, bad encoded
      files, etc.)

Since I'm not on the Internet with my Amiga, I'd appreciate bug reports if
either the email or newsgroup systems don't work. I think they're working OK,
but I can't check easily.

Mail all bug reports to me at: tone_20@my-Deja.com.

@endnode

@node History "History of MPackMUI..."
                                    @{b}History@{ub}

Changes since V1.0:

    * Added MIME types
    * Code clean-up
    * Addition of MUI info
    * Removed ASL tooltypes (not needed for OS 3.5)
    * Improved ASL requesting (old path now re-entered automatically)
    * Improved MPack/Munpack execution error-handling

@endnode

@node About "A few technical notes on MPackMUI"
                                 @{b}About MPackMUI@{ub}

MPackMUI has been fully tested with Enforcer and Mungwall, and has been checked
for memory leaks.

MPackMUI was developed using:

                * Storm C Compiler --> Wahay! I got Storm C at last.

                * GoldEd           --> The BEST text editor ever written.

                * Enforcer         --> The original and the best.

                * Mungwall         --> Still works gr8 for me.

                * Sushi            --> Damn useful.

I've included source code for all you prospecting coders out there to play with.
I believe that with the Amiga in it's current state, it is necessary to
encourage more programmers by giving them example source. In this way, I hope
that other people can learn from what I myself have learned, much of which came
from studying other people's source. I hope that, if you are a programmer, you
will consider doing this as well.

The source can be compiled straight into Storm C (using the supplied project
file), although the file paths may need changing. With a little modification,
the source should also work on other compilers. The code is all yours to play
with, have fun!

@endnode

